<br>
Speaking as one who plays on the Karana server,<br>
<br>
Do 60+ Enchanters sit in the Nexus/Bazaar and shout, &quot;Buffing KEI for 100pp&quot;?  Yes, I pretty much see it every time I pass through there.  What's so bad about that?  If you don't agree with the price, it's simple.  Just don't pay and get a KEI from someone else.  That person still has a right to charge whatever they want for buffing their KEI.<br>
<br>
I personally feel that being a KEI capable enchanter has been more of a pain-in-the-butt to my enjoyment of EQ then anything else so far in my two-and-a-half years of playing.  Why?  I really don't like beggars.  Forget begs for rezzes, begs for ports, begs for shaman buffs... if you are a KEI capable enchanter (who doesn't like to hide behind /anon /role) then you are going to get the most begs per day then any of these.  I've never asked for any pp when I give out my KEI even though I paid 80k for my KEI scroll.  Usually a few times a month I will go to places like LOIO, Oasis, or the Karanas and buff lowbies with KEI/shissar just because it puts a smile on my face to see how truly appreciative they are of it (it's usually the 50's and 60's crowd I dislike.. most expect KEI from me regardless of where I am or what I'm doing).<br>
<br>
So I can hardly imagine anyone thinking this KEI Enc is greedy.  Tired and frustrated?  Yes, you could say that.  Sometimes I just don't even reply to the seemingly non-stop begs for KEI.<br>
<br>
Anyway, maybe there are some &quot;greedy&quot; Encs out there.   But Damerr??  Just remember that there are still some old-school enchanters out there who did start out fighting rats and bats with a guild tattered robe and a little dagger, and have earned every piece of pp or loot they have in their possession.<br>
<br>
Oh one final note to all you people who do ask for KEI from an Enchanter.  Please don't be /anon or /roleplaying when you ask.  Maybe nobody else feels this way, but I just find it a great annoyance when someone is hiding their class and level (more then likely to avoid beggars) begs for me to buff them.<br>
<br>
Well, I'll stop rambling on and on now.<br>
<br>
Take care,<br>
<br>
